Description: Sit start with two underclings.  The large unattached rock right at the base of the boulder is off for feet! Work your left hand around and then up to a small slopey rail. Bring your right hand up to the right edge of the original feature.This next move is the crux. A high left heel / whole foot smear on the feature helps!Either make a big move with your right hand out to a crimpy sidepull, or make a weird side mantle move with your right hand and slap it way up to the slopey lip.  Match the slopey lip and top it out without using the really good jugs to the left.

Description: Start: Standing - Both hands on good crimps about half way up the right side of the dihedral, your left foot on a decent sloper and your right foot flagged around the arete.First move is into a sharp thumb-press mantel with your left hand.  Then, match your right foot on the starting foot hold and get a left-hand-foot match on the mantel.  From there, bring your left hand up into an 'Okay' left-side pull crimp.  Finally, get your right hand up to a good crimp, just to the right of the side-pull; get your right foot on the staring hand holds and top out on the boulder.***Note - This may already be an established route but, I have not been able to find any information on it.

Description: Start: Standing - Both hands on good crimps about half way up the right side of the dihedral, your left foot on a decent sloper and your right foot flagged around the arete.Beginning of this is the same as Spider's Nest Dihedral:First move is into a sharp thumb-press mantel with your left hand.  Then, match your right foot on the starting foot hold and get a left-hand-foot match on the mantel.  From there, bring your left hand up into an 'Okay' left-side pull crimp.  Next, get your right hand up to a good crimp, just to the right of the side-pull.Where it differs:Once your right hand in on the good crimp, left hand out to a sharp crimp, over a slopey rail(this should make sense when you feel the hold); bring right foot in, match and then throw for the top of the boulder, there is a good rail.  Finally, get a high left foot on the lower part of the ledge and top out.***Note - This may already be an established route but, I have not been able to find any information on it.

Location: Devil's Half Acre > Sourland Mountain Preserve > * bouldering mid-state NJ > d. Mid-state > New Jersey
Description: A short but fun slab climb with tiny, almost non-existent footholds. Start on the horizontal crack a little more than halfway up the boulder. The really good foothold on the left, at the start of the problem is off; the first move was way too easy with that foot.  The right arete is also off. From the start, go right hand to a solid crimp, then left hand to a gaston. Get your left foot up super high to the starting crack, and move to the good horizontal crack near the top of the boulder. Match, and top out.The crux move is definitely moving from the gaston to the horizontal crack.  The best way we found to make this move was to get your left foot super high.The holds are not terrible - most of them are tiny crimps, but this is a slab problem.  What makes this climb tough is the absolute lack of feet; make use of any small divot in the rock that you can.

Description: Climb the beautiful gold and black arete on its left side to the horizontal. Move up on jugs and swing further up and right around to the jug on the slab. Finish up the hollow flake. Watch out for fragile holds up high anddo not fall on the topout. When dialed this problem climbs like a nice 5.11 and is a great warmup, but remains a serious undertaking.

Location: Roaring Rocks > Sourland Mountain Preserve > * bouldering mid-state NJ > d. Mid-state > New Jersey
Description: Maybe the best moderate highball in New Jersey. This problem has it all: a natural line up an impressive boulder with great moves on cool holds. The rock quality is very good and the crux getting over the bulge is exciting and just tricky enough. It is the exact opposite of all the short and contrived diabase problems with bad landings. If you find this problem too easy just step right to Blood Sport for another exhilarating classic.The problem starts standing with the left hand on a pinch and right hand on an edge. Make some interesting moves on good holds following the bulge up and right to join Blood Sport. Fight your way over the bulge on some tricky incuts and top out. The crux is about 10 feet off the ground but the fall is clean and the landing is flat. The topout slab is easy.

Description: Super short problem on the slab.Beta:First scramble up onto the big ledge. Start hands on the two big edges. Put right foot in the big crack down just above the ledge you start on, then reach left foot out to a juggy thing on the arete  (lower arrow). Stand up and go left hand to the slopey hold on the arete, then bring your right hand up to the tiny pocket. Next, a SUPER high right foot to where your right hand started. Reach right hand up to the top, bring your left foot up to the edge your left hand started on, and then you're basically there.

Route: The Wave / Stuart Arete - Stand Start
Location: Witherspoon Woods Boulders > * bouldering mid-state NJ > d. Mid-state > New Jersey
Route name: The Wave Stuart Arete Stand Start
Description: Start with your left hand on a decent edge and your right hand on a pinch just below the jug. Bump up to the jug and continue to the slopey lip. For full value, don't traverse right at the lip, but instead top out straight up. You can do it!Alternate Description:Standing in front of the prow. Right hand on the jug on the prow. Left hand out to the left. Go onto the right side for an easier variation. Go left and top out is harder.

Location: Witherspoon Woods Boulders > * bouldering mid-state NJ > d. Mid-state > New Jersey
Description: Sit start with your right hand on a bad sloper and left hand on a vaguely ball-like sloper. There are several options for getting to the pinch, some involving a barely-there sloper intermediate, and some involving a powerful and extended gaston. Once you wrap the jug with your right hand, it's pretty much in the bag (assuming you can climb The Wave stand).The ideal conditions for an ascent of this sloper testpiece are a crisp 80-degree day in June, with full humidity, and nursing a hangover from Princeton Reunions. While we conservatively grade this problem V8, there have been murmurs that the true grade is closer to V10. To those murmurers I say: Thank you. You're very kind.

Location: Witherspoon Woods Boulders > * bouldering mid-state NJ > d. Mid-state > New Jersey
Description: Climb Stuart Arete into the stand start.  Then crimp, heel hook, toe hook and swing your way left to reverse Stuart Right.  Finish as for Bum Rap.  It climbs quite well even if it is a little cramped with the tree.  Felt about the same in difficulty as Stuart Right.  It will likely be harder for shorter climbers but there are other options they could use for the traverse.

Location: Witherspoon Woods Boulders > * bouldering mid-state NJ > d. Mid-state > New Jersey
Description: This boulder adds a sit start to the "cave problem". Start with your hands on two low crimps with solid feet on the inside right of the cave. Work through a couple good crimps and then make a big move into the starting ledge of the cave problem. With an awkward heel hook and undercling slap to a sloper. From here make a big move to a good edge over the lip. Traverse left through small crimps (although you can top out going straight up from the crimps, I have done this finish and don't think it is any harder, and it seems like a shame to waste the fun holds you get exiting to the left) and the occasional feet to top out on the left side above a smaller boulder.
